Decidedly off season. Film dump from a nearly empty Montauk, New York. Back in the 50s, my dad and his father and brothers would come from the Bronx and camp on the beach near (or at) Ditch Plains. I can only imagine what it looked like back then. Having spent so much time there as a kid myself and then into my 20s in a literal endless sea of crowds (and before I moved to Southern California), it was nice to go there now and enjoy the quiet of the off-season. It’s a special place and I’m super thankful for clients who bring me to my absolute favorite places on earth and the friends we make along the way. 🤘🏼

I’ve always wanted to start a studio-visit project and was honored when @rainerarts allowed me to come photograph him at his studio putting some work into his stunning portrait of legend Rick Rubin. I think as artists it’s important to a comfortable creative space to work and the spaces we create have always been fascinating to me because they’re all so personal and all so vastly different. Looking forward to exploring this project more.

A couple weekends ago @katemoorephoto, @oliveschell, and I rented a camper van and drove up through Yosemite and then down and over to Big Sur for the weekend. The weather was stunning, the views were fantastic, and it was a great introduction to our first Vanlife weekend - and a nice change from cooking on the ground and sleeping in the back of the Land Cruiser. Thanks to @outdoorsy, @tbrentals, @hipcamp, and @harvesthosts for such a cool experience. Not an ad, just a happy customer. Part II coming soon.

If you’re a photographer, I don’t think you could ever escape hearing someone say “it’s overcast isn’t that better for photos?“ Truth is, living in LA our overcast days are very few and far between so it’s easy to forget just how true the sentiment happens to be. And while I do love our 300+ days of sun a year; there’s something special about making photos on partly cloudy or overcast day. Glad I got to spend it with one of the best. @meaganlee_1
